questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Read the following Assertion (A) and Reasoning (R) and choose the correct option.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assertion (A)&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;Chola king Rajendra I built a Shiva temple in his capital and filled it with prized statues seized from defeated rulers. Sultan Mahmud of Ghazni, a contemporary of Rajendra I, also attacked the temples of defeated kings and looted their wealth and idols during his campaigns in the subcontinent.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reason (R)&lt;/strong&gt;: In the political culture of the middle ages most rulers displayed their political might and military success by attacking and looting the places of worship of defeated rulers.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;b&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;oth (A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During the medieval period, especially in South Asia, many rulers displayed their power and military prowess by constructing &lt;strong&gt;grand temples, palaces, and forts&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These buildings often served as a symbol of their &lt;strong&gt;political legitimacy and authority.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition to building their own structures, they also often seized valuable items such as statues, idols, and other treasures from defeated rulers and placed them in their own buildings as a sign of their conquest.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rajendra I&lt;/strong&gt;, the Chola king, was known for his military campaigns and conquests.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He built a grand temple for Lord Shiva in his capital city of &lt;strong&gt;Gangaikonda Cholapuram&lt;/strong&gt; and filled it with valuable statues and treasures seized from defeated rulers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly, &lt;strong&gt;Mahmud of Ghazni, &lt;/strong&gt;a Muslim ruler who invaded and conquered parts of the Indian subcontinent, attacked numerous temples and looted them of their valuable treasures, including idols made of precious metals and gems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;The political culture of the medieval period in South Asia involved a display of military might through the construction of grand structures and the seizure of valuable items from defeated rulers.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;both assertion (A) and reason (R) are true, and reason (R) provides a correct explanation for assertion (A)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Put in sequence the process of temple town formation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Pilgrims visited the temples and made donations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Large number of priests, workers, traders settled near temples.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Rulers endowed temples with grants of land and money.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(D) Temple authorities used wealth to finance trade and banking.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct chronological sequence is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(C), (A), (D) and (B).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Temple towns represent a very important pattern of urbanisation, the process by which cities develop.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Temples were often central to the economy and society.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rulers built temples to demonstrate their devotion to various deities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They also &lt;strong&gt;endowed temples with grants of land and money to carry out elaborate rituals&lt;/strong&gt;, feed pilgrims and priests and celebrate festivals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pilgrims who flocked to the temples also made donations.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Temple authorities used their wealth to finance trade and banking.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gradually &lt;strong&gt;a large number of priests, workers, artisans, traders, etc. settled near the temple &lt;/strong&gt;to cater to its needs and those of the pilgrims.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus grew temple towns.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Towns emerged around temples such as those of Bhillasvamin (Bhilsa or Vidisha in Madhya Pradesh), and Somnath in Gujarat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Other important temple towns included Kanchipuram and Madurai in Tamil Nadu and Tirupati in Andhra Pradesh&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Hence we conclude that the correct chronological sequence is&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt; (C), (A), (D) and (B).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statements are true about the making of regional cultures in the eighteenth century?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) It is a product of intermixing of local traditions with ideas from outside.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) It is a highly localised practice specific to a region.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) It was always confined by political boundaries.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;statements &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A) and (B) are true&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; &lt;/span&gt;about the making of regional cultures in the eighteenth century.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;making of regional cultures in the eighteenth century&lt;/strong&gt; was often the &lt;strong&gt;result of the intermixing of local traditions with external influences&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;This could be due to trade, migration, or colonialism, which introduced new ideas and practices that were then adapted and incorporated into local cultures. Hence, &lt;strong&gt;statement (A) is true.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regional cultures in the eighteenth century were often highly localised&lt;/strong&gt;, with distinctive customs, languages, and cultural practices that were &lt;strong&gt;specific to a particular region or community. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;This was due to a variety of factors, including geography, history, and social and political structures. Thus,&lt;strong&gt; statement (B) is true.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regional cultures in the eighteenth century were not always confined by political boundaries,&lt;/strong&gt; and often transcended them. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;For example, the spread of Sufism in South Asia created a shared cultural space that cut across political and linguistic divides, uniting people across regions and empires. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;Similarly, the spread of Buddhism from India to Southeast Asia created a cultural network that linked different regions and societies. Therefore, &lt;strong&gt;statement (C&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;) is not true.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (55, 65, 81);   white-space: pre-wrap; background-color:  (247, 247, 248);&quot;&gt;Therefore, we can conclude that the &lt;/span&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;statements &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A) and (B) are true&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color:  (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;about the making of regional cultures in the eighteenth century.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Kabir challenged the formal religions of his time by&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;ridiculing the priestly classes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;nbsp;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kabir believed in a formless Supreme God and preached that the only path to salvation was through &lt;strong&gt;bhakti or devotion&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kabir drew his followers from both Hindus and Muslims.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kabir&amp;rsquo;s teachings were based on a complete, indeed vehement, rejection of the major religious traditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;His teachings openly &lt;strong&gt;ridiculed &lt;/strong&gt;all forms of external worship of both Brahmanical Hinduism and Islam, the &lt;strong&gt;pre-eminence of the priestly classes&lt;/strong&gt; and the caste system.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The language of his poetry was a form of spoken Hindi widely understood by ordinary people.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;He also sometimes used &lt;strong&gt;cryptic language&lt;/strong&gt;, which is difficult to follow.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence we conclude that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Kabir challenged the formal religions of his time by&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;ridiculing the priestly classes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;The English cultivated indigo in______.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Jamaica&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) India&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Caribbean Islands&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(D) Venezuela&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A) and (B).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Blue is usually&amp;nbsp;produced from a plant called &lt;strong&gt;indigo.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cloth dyers, however, preferred indigo as a dye.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Indigo produced a rich blue colour, whereas the dye from Woad was pale and dull.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;European cloth manufacturers&amp;nbsp;had to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;depend on another plant&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;called woad to make violet and blue dyes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The British used a variety of methods to expand the cultivation of blue&amp;nbsp;that they needed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;By the seventeenth century, European cloth producers persuaded their governments to relax the ban on indigo imports.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The French began cultivating indigo in St Domingue in the Caribbean islands, the Portuguese in Brazil, the&lt;strong&gt; English in Jamaica&lt;/strong&gt;, and the Spanish in Venezuela.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Indigo plantations also came up in many parts of North America.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is likely that the blue dye used in the Morris prints in &lt;strong&gt;nineteenth-century Britain &lt;/strong&gt;was manufactured from indigo plants &lt;strong&gt;cultivated in India.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;India was the biggest supplier of indigo&lt;/strong&gt; in the world at that time.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we can conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct option is&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;(A) and (B)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;The Birsa Movement had important consequences, such as:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Colonial government had to introduce new forest laws to safeguard the tribal land from dikus.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Tribal chiefs got new land titles under the British land settlements.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Tribal people showed the capacity to protest against colonial rule.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct option:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A), and (C).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;British&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;arrested &lt;strong&gt;Birsa Munda&lt;/strong&gt; in 1895, convicted him on charges of rioting and jailed him for two years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When Birsa was released in 1897, he began touring the villages to gather support.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He used traditional symbols and language to rouse people, urging them to destroy &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;Ravana&amp;rdquo; (dikus and the Europeans)&lt;/strong&gt; and establish a kingdom under his leadership.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1900, Birsa died of cholera and the movement faded out.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, the movement was significant in at least two ways.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;First &amp;ndash; it forced the colonial government to introduce laws &lt;/strong&gt;so that the land of the tribals could not be easily taken over by dikus.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Second &amp;ndash; it showed once again that the tribal people had the capacity to protest &lt;/strong&gt;against injustice and express their anger against colonial rule.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;They did this in their own specific way, inventing their own rituals and symbols of struggle.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A), and (C).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Read the statements &amp;#39;A&amp;#39; and &amp;#39;B&amp;#39; on Mahatma Gandhi&amp;#39;s views on medium of education :&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A) :&lt;/strong&gt; Gandhi strongly felt that Indian languages ought to be the medium of teaching.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(B) &lt;/strong&gt;: Education in English made Indians, strangers in their own lands.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct answer of the following:&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;both&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A) and (B) are true and (B) explains (A).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahatma Gandhi&lt;/strong&gt; argued that colonial education created a sense of inferiority in the minds of Indians.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It made them see&lt;strong&gt; Western civilisation&lt;/strong&gt; as superior, and destroyed the pride they had in their own culture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;There was &lt;strong&gt;poison in this education&lt;/strong&gt;, said Mahatma Gandhi, it was sinful, it &lt;strong&gt;enslaved Indians&lt;/strong&gt;, it cast an evil spell on them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Charmed by the West, appreciating everything that came from the West, Indians educated in these institutions began admiring British rule.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mahatma Gandhi wanted an education that could help Indians recover their sense of &lt;strong&gt;dignity and self-respect.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During the &lt;strong&gt;national movement&lt;/strong&gt; he urged students to leave educational institutions in order to show to the British that Indians were no longer willing to be enslaved.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahatma Gandhi strongly felt that Indian languages ought to be the medium of teaching&lt;/strong&gt;. Hence, &lt;strong&gt;statement (A) is true.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Education in English crippled Indians,&lt;/strong&gt; distanced them from their own social surroundings, and &lt;strong&gt;made them &amp;ldquo;strangers in their own lands&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;. Thus,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;statement (B) is true.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Speaking a foreign tongue, despising local culture, the &lt;strong&gt;English educated did not know how to relate to the masses.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Western education&lt;/strong&gt;, Mahatma Gandhi said, &lt;strong&gt;focused on reading and writing rather than oral knowledge&lt;/strong&gt;; it valued textbooks rather than lived experience and practical knowledge.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;He argued that education ought to develop a person&amp;rsquo;s mind and soul.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Literacy &amp;ndash; or simply learning to read and write &amp;ndash; by itself did not count as education.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;People had to work with their hands, learn a craft, and know how different things operated.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;This would develop their mind and their capacity to understand.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Based on the above discussion, we can conclude that both&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A) and (B) are true and (B) explains (A).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Henry Derozio was the leader of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Young Bengal Movement&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;nbsp;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Henry Louis Vivian Derozio&lt;/strong&gt;, a teacher at Hindu College, Calcutta, in the 1820s, promoted radical ideas and encouraged his pupils to question all authority.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Referred to as the Young Bengal Movement, his students attacked tradition and custom, demanded education for women and campaigned for the&lt;strong&gt; freedom of thought and expression.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The movement had a significant impact on Indian society and culture, particularly in Bengal, where it helped to pave the way for the Bengal Renaissance, a period of intellectual and cultural awakening that saw the emergence of &lt;strong&gt;new forms of art, literature, and social reform movements.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Some of the notable members of the Young Bengal Movement included &lt;strong&gt;Michael Madhusudan Dutt, Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay, and Ishwar Chandra Vidyasagar&lt;/strong&gt;, who went on to become influential figures in Indian literature and social reform.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence we conclude that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Henry Derozio was the leader of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Young Bengal Movement.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Read the following statements and choose the appropriate option:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) In 1919 Gandhiji gave a call for Satyagraha against the Rowlatt Act that the British had just passed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Mohammad Ali Jinnah however supported the Rowlatt Act.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A) is true but (B) is false.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;nbsp;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1919, &lt;strong&gt;Gandhiji gave a call for a satyagraha &lt;/strong&gt;against the Rowlatt Act that the British had just passed.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Act curbed fundamental rights such as freedom of expression and strengthened police powers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mahatma Gandhi,&lt;strong&gt; Mohammad Ali Jinnah &lt;/strong&gt;and others felt that the government had no right to restrict people&amp;rsquo;s basic freedoms.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They criticised the Act as &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;devilish&amp;rdquo; and tyrannical&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Thus &lt;strong&gt;statement B is incorrect.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Gandhiji asked the Indian people to observe 6 April 1919 as a day of &lt;strong&gt;non-violent opposition&lt;/strong&gt; to this Act, as a day of &amp;ldquo;humiliation and prayer&amp;rdquo; and hartal (strike). So &lt;strong&gt;statement A is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Satyagraha Sabhas were set up to launch the movement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;The Rowlatt Satyagraha turned out to be the first all-India struggle against the British government although it was largely restricted to cities.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence we conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A) is true but (B) is false.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;They felt that the British had respect for the ideals of freedom and justice.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Leaders such as &lt;strong&gt;Bipin Chandra Pal, Bal Gangadhar Tilak and Lala Lajpat Rai &lt;/strong&gt;were beginning to explore more radical objectives and methods.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They&lt;strong&gt; criticised the Moderates for their &amp;ldquo;politics of prayers&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They emphasised the importance of self-reliance and constructive work.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They argued that people must rely on their own strength,&lt;strong&gt; not on the &amp;ldquo;good&amp;rdquo; intentions of the government;&lt;/strong&gt; people must fight for swaraj.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Tilak raised the slogan,&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;Freedom is my birthright and I shall have it!&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;But they &lt;strong&gt;never &lt;/strong&gt;felt that the British had respect for the ideals of freedom and justice.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Instead, they believed that the Britishers never gave Swaraj in accordance with their way.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;They felt that the British had respect for the ideals of freedom and justice.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#39;Unlike neighbouring countries like Pakistan and Sri Lanka, India handled the linguistic problems very carefully after Independence.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which of the following statement/statements justify/justifies this?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) The Indian government respected all the regional languages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Regional languages were given the freedom to flourish.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Hindi was not imposed on any other regional languages.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(D) The government avoided language-related problems.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A), (B) and (C) only.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&amp;nbsp;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The statement &amp;quot;India handled the linguistic problems very carefully after Independence&amp;quot; suggests that the Indian &lt;strong&gt;government took a cautious and sensitive approach&lt;/strong&gt; towards managing the linguistic diversity in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The statement further suggests that the Indian &lt;strong&gt;government did not impose Hindi on any other regional language&lt;/strong&gt;, and respected and encouraged the development of all regional languages.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, options&lt;strong&gt; (A), (B) and (C) all align &lt;/strong&gt;with the statement and justify why India&amp;#39;s handling of linguistic problems after independence was careful.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Option&lt;strong&gt; (D) is incorrect&lt;/strong&gt; because it suggests that the government avoided language-related problems, which is not explicitly stated in the statement.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So we can conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A), (B) and (C) only.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;B.R. Ambedkar led the 1927 temple entry movement because _______.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) people who were called &amp;#39;untouchables&amp;#39; by the casteist society were not allowed inside the temple.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) He had already become Buddhist and wanted Buddhism to be considered a sect of Hinduism.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) He wanted Hindu society reorganised on principles of equality.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct option is&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(A)&amp;nbsp;and (C).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ambedkar&lt;/strong&gt; was born into a Mahar family.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a child, he experienced what caste prejudice meant in everyday life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In school, he was forced to sit outside the classroom on the ground and was &lt;strong&gt;not allowed to drink water&lt;/strong&gt; from taps that upper-caste children used.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After finishing school, he got a fellowship to go to the US for higher studies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On his return to India in 1919, he wrote extensively about&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 1927, Ambedkar started a temple entry movement, in which his Mahar caste followers participated.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Brahman priests were outraged&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also, &lt;strong&gt;Dalits are not permitted to enter&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ambedkar led &lt;strong&gt;three&lt;/strong&gt; such movements for temple entry between 1927 and 1935.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;His &lt;strong&gt;aim was to make everyone&lt;/strong&gt; see the power of caste prejudices within society.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence we conclude that t&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;he correct option is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A)&amp;nbsp;and (C).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Read the following statements about Moon.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Only one side of the moon is visible to us on the earth.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) The time taken for moon to complete a spin on its axis and the time taken to orbit the earth is exactly same.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct option.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;Both (A) and (B) are true, and (B) is the correct explanation of (A).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(A) Only one side of the moon is visible to us on the earth.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Only one side of the moon, known as the near side, is visible to us on the earth.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because the &lt;strong&gt;moon takes approximately the same amount of time to rotate on its axis as it does to orbit the earth&lt;/strong&gt;, a phenomenon known as synchronous rotation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a result, the same side of the moon always faces the earth, while the other side, known as the far side or &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;dark side,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; remains hidden from view.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement (A) is true.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(B) The time taken for moon to complete a spin on its axis and the time taken to orbit the earth is exactly same.​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The time taken for the moon to complete one spin on its axis and the time taken to orbit the earth is&amp;nbsp;exactly the same.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Solved] Read the following statement carefully and choose the correc&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/22/06/F1_Madhuri_Teaching_27.06.2022_D1.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This means that the same side of the moon always faces the earth, as explained in statement (A).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Cold current&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;The Labrador Current is a cold ocean current that flows southward along the coast of eastern Canada, extending as far south as the Grand Banks of Newfoundland. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is a component of the North Atlantic Gyre, which is a large circular ocean current system that includes the Gulf Stream and other currents.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Labrador Current is formed by the mixing of cold water from the Arctic and subarctic regions with the warm water of the Gulf Stream.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cold water originates from the Labrador Sea, which is located to the north of the current&amp;#39;s path.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Labrador Sea is an area of intense oceanic mixing and upwelling, where cold, nutrient-rich water rises to the surface and is exposed to the atmosphere.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This process results in the formation of a cold, dense layer of water that flows southward along the eastern coast of Canada.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Labrador Current is an important component of the oceanic and atmospheric circulation of the region.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It has a significant impact on the climate and weather patterns of eastern Canada and the northeastern United States.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cold water carried by the current lowers the temperature and humidity of the coastal regions, leading to cooler and drier conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The current also influences the formation of sea ice and the movement of marine species, including whales, seals, and fish.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In addition to its scientific significance, the Labrador Current has played an important role in the history and culture of eastern Canada.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It has shaped the development of coastal communities and the fisheries that rely on the region&amp;#39;s abundant marine resources.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The current has also been a subject of fascination and inspiration for artis&lt;/strong&gt;ts, writers, and explorers who have been drawn to the rugged and wild beauty of the eastern Canadian coast&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://static.prepp.in/public/image/085e3a22f9c0da42ac14506dd6fa308f.jpeg?tr=w-406,h-317,c-force&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are factors of soil formation?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Altitude and slope&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Flora and Fauna&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Temperature and Rainfall&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(D) Time&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer&amp;nbsp;is:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol start=&quot;4&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All (A), (B), (C) and (D)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Soil formation is a complex process that involves the interaction of several factors. These factors include:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A) Altitude and slope: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Altitude and slope influence soil formation by affecting temperature, precipitation, and the rate of erosion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Higher altitudes tend to be colder and receive more precipitation, which can lead to the formation of thinner soils with less organic matter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Slope can also affect soil formation by influencing the rate of erosion and the amount of sunlight that reaches the soil.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B) Flora and Fauna: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plants and animals play an important role in soil formation by contributing organic matter, nutrients, and physical structure to the soil.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For example, the roots of plants help to hold soil in place and create channels for water to infiltrate, while the decomposition of plant and animal remains adds organic matter to the soil.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C) Temperature and Rainfall: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Temperature and rainfall are important factors in soil formation, as they influence the rate of weathering and the decomposition of organic matter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Higher temperatures and more rainfall tend to lead to faster weathering and decomposition, which can result in the formation of thicker soils with more organic matter.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D) Time:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Soil formation is a slow process that can take thousands of years.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The longer a soil has been forming, the more developed it is likely to be, with thicker layers and more diverse microbial communities.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, all options (A), (B), (C) and (D) are correct factors of soil formation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following statements about waterways and choose the appropriate option.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Waterways are the most commonly used means of transport for short distances.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Navigable rivers and lakes are used as inland water ways.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Durban and Cape Town are important ports in Africa.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;(B) and (C) are true&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;(A) Roads, not waterways,&amp;nbsp;are the most commonly used means of transport for short distances.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This statement is incorrect&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The four major means of transport are roadways, railways, waterways and airways. The most commonly used means of transport especially for short distances are roads. They can be metalled (pucca) and unmetalled (kutcha)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(B) Navigable rivers and lakes are used as inland waterways.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This statement is also true.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Navigable rivers and lakes are used as inland waterways in many countries around the world.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Inland waterways are an important component of the transportation system, especially for transporting goods over short to medium distances.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Navigable rivers and lakes are typically used for shipping of bulk commodities, such as grain, coal, and petroleum.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;(C) Durban and Cape Town are important ports in Africa.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This statement is true.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Durban and Cape Town are two of the most important ports in Africa.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Durban is the busiest port in South Africa and the third busiest port in Africa, handling a large volume of cargo and serving as a major gateway for trade with Asia and Europe.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cape Town is also an important port, serving the Western Cape region and offering connections to the rest of Africa.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore,&amp;nbsp; statements&amp;nbsp; (B), and (C) are true.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the following mineral deposits:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Limestone deposits of caucasus region of France&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Manganese deposition of Georgia and Ukraine&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Phosphate beds of Algeria&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Which kind of rocks holds these deposits?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The following types of rocks hold the mentioned mineral deposits are&amp;nbsp;Sedimentary rocks.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Limestone deposits of the Caucasus region&lt;/strong&gt; of France are held in &lt;strong&gt;sedimentary rocks.&lt;/strong&gt; Limestone itself is a sedimentary rock that forms from the accumulation of calcium carbonate shells and skeletons of marine organisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Manganese deposits of Georgia and Ukraine &lt;/strong&gt;are held in &lt;strong&gt;sedimentary rocks&lt;/strong&gt;, specifically in sedimentary manganese ore formations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Phosphate beds of Algeria&lt;/strong&gt; are held in &lt;strong&gt;sedimentary rocks.&lt;/strong&gt; Phosphate rock is a sedimentary rock that contains high amounts of phosphate minerals, usually apatite. These rocks are formed from the accumulation of organic remains and minerals in marine environments.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Consider the statements (A) and (B) about conventional energy and choose the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement (A)&lt;/strong&gt; : Conventional source of energy are those whose occurence is in limited local area and which have been in common use for a long time.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Statement (B) &lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;Only fossil fuels are sources of conventional energy.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;Option 2) Both (A) and (B) are false.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assertion (A): Conventional source of energy are those whose occurrence is in limited local area and which have been in common use for a long time.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The latter part of the statement, about being in common use for a long time, is accurate for conventional energy sources.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, the first part, stating that their occurrence is limited to local areas, is not accurate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Conventional energy sources like coal, oil, and natural gas are found and utilized in various parts of the world, not confined to specific localities.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Reason (R): Only fossil fuels are sources of conventional energy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is false because while fossil fuels like coal, oil, and natural gas are indeed conventional sources of energy, they are not the only ones.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Conventional sources also include nuclear energy and traditional biomass like wood and agricultural residues used for heating and cooking, among others.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41); font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Therefore, the correct choice would be Option 2) Both (A) and (B) are false.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following pair / pairs, is / are correctly matched.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Maize :&amp;nbsp;High temperature and light rainfall&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Cotton :&amp;nbsp;Moderate temperature and rainfall&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Jute :&amp;nbsp;High temperature and heavy rainfall&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Choose the correct option.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct option is (C) Jute: High temperature and heavy rainfall&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jute is a crop that requires a hot and &lt;strong&gt;humid climate with heavy rainfall.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is primarily grown in the &lt;strong&gt;Indian subcontinent&lt;/strong&gt;, especially in areas with &lt;strong&gt;high humidity, such as the Ganges Delta.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Jute is used for making various products such as sacks, bags, ropes, and carpets.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Maize, on the other hand, is a crop that can grow in a variety of climatic conditions. However, it grows best in areas with &lt;strong&gt;high temperature and moderate rainfall.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cotton is a crop that grows well in &lt;strong&gt;moderate temperatures and requires a moderate amount of rainfall&lt;/strong&gt;. It is grown in many parts of the world, including the United States, China, and India.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Shortest day and longest night.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Earth&amp;#39;s axial tilt causes the variation in daylight hours and the changing of th&lt;/strong&gt;e seasons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The tilt is approximately 23.5 degrees relative to the Earth&amp;#39;s orbital plane around the Sun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As Earth orbits the Sun, the axial tilt causes different parts of the Earth to receive varying amounts of sunlight throughout the year, resulting in the seasons.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;On June 21st, the Northern Hemisphere experiences the summer solstice, which is the longest day and shortest night of the year.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This occurs because the North Pole is tilted towards the Sun, and as a result, the Sun appears at its highest point in the sky at solar noon.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This leads to more daylight hours and warmer temperatures.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At the same time, the Southern Hemisphere experiences the winter solstice, which is the shortest day and longest night of the year.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This occurs because the South Pole is tilted away from the Sun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As a result, the Sun appears lower in the sky, leading to fewer daylight hours and colder temperatures.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;So, on June 21st in the Southern Hemisphere, the correct statement is: Shortest day and longest night&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When the Prime Meridian of Greenwich has the sun at the highest point in the sky, all the places along this meridian will have Mid-day.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When the &lt;strong&gt;Prime Meridian of Greenwich&lt;/strong&gt; has the &lt;strong&gt;sun at the highest point in the sky&lt;/strong&gt;, it will be&lt;strong&gt; noon (12:00 pm) at this location.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because the Prime Meridian is the reference line for time zones and is defined as the line of longitude that passes through the &lt;strong&gt;Royal Observatory in Greenwich, London, UK.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;All the places along this meridian, which includes &lt;strong&gt;the UK and parts of western Europe and Africa&lt;/strong&gt;, will have the same local time as the Prime Meridian.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This means that it will also be noon at all these places when the sun is at the highest point in the sky at the Prime Meridian.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, it is important to note that other places located in different time zones will have different local times when the Prime Meridian has the sun at the highest point in the sky.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because the Earth is divided into 24 time zones, each of which is 15 degrees of longitude wide and has a time difference of one hour from its neighboring time zones.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, places located to the east or west of the Prime Meridian will have different local times based on their respective time zones.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Arctic Circle&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;lies at&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class=&quot;math-tex&quot;&gt;\(66\frac{1}{2}\)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;deg; North of the equator.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;At 66.5&amp;deg; north of the equator lies the Arctic Circle, an imaginary line that circles the Earth at approximately 66.5 degrees north latitude.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is the northernmost point where the sun can be seen above the horizon during the summer solstice, and the southernmost point where the midnight sun can be seen during the winter solstice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The region within the Arctic Circle is known as the Arctic, which includes parts of Norway, Sweden, Finland, Russia, the United States, Canada, Greenland, and Iceland.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;Solved] With regard to the value of latitudes of important places, w&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/03/F1_Bobita_Anil_12.03.21_D2.png&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are the &lt;strong&gt;Tropic of Cancer (23.5 degrees north of the equator)&lt;/strong&gt; and the &lt;strong&gt;Tropic of Capricorn (23.5 degrees south of the equator).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The line near the &lt;strong&gt;North Pole is the Arctic Circle (66.5 degrees N)&lt;/strong&gt;, and the line near the &lt;strong&gt;South Pole is the Antarctic circle (66.5 degrees S).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Middle Himalayas are known as Himachal.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Himalayas are divided into three main regions based on their altitude and topography: the Outer Himalayas or Shiwalik, the Lesser Himalayas or Middle Himalayas,&lt;/strong&gt; and the Greater Himalayas or High Himalayas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Middle Himalayas, also known as the Lesser Himalayas, are located between the Outer Himalayas and the Greater Himalayas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This region is characterized by high ridges, deep valleys, and a mix of forested and alpine landscapes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Middle Himalayas are also home to several important rivers, including the Ganges, Yamuna, and Brahmaputra.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In this context, Himachal refers to the region of the Middle Himalayas in the Indian state of Himachal Pradesh.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/qImage68c941f3cdc386bf7c74f20c.png&quot; style=&quot;height: 281px; width: 380px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following are forms of precipitation ?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Flood&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Snow&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Hail&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(D) Sleet&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;(B), (C), (D)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Precipitation is any form of water that falls from the atmosphere and reaches the Earth&amp;#39;s surface. It can take several forms, including rain, snow, sleet, and hail.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A) Flood is not a form of precipitation&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Floods occur when there is an excessive amount of water in a river or other body of water, causing it to overflow onto the surrounding land.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B) Snow is a form of precipitation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;that occurs when water vapor in the atmosphere freezes into ice crystals. These ice crystals combine to form snowflakes, which fall to the ground as snow.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;C) Hail is a form of precipitation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;that occurs during thunderstorms, when strong updrafts carry raindrops high into the atmosphere, where they freeze into ice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These ice particles can then grow larger as they are carried up and down by the storm&amp;#39;s updrafts, eventually falling to the ground as hailstones.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;D) Sleet is a form of precipitation&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;that occurs when raindrops fall through a layer of freezing air near the ground, causing them to freeze into ice pellets before reaching the ground.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the forms of precipitation are rain, snow, and sleet, making option (2) (A), (B), (D) the correct answer&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon dioxide (CO2) is known as the greenhouse gas.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Greenhouse gases are gases that trap heat in the Earth&amp;#39;s atmosphere and contribute to the greenhouse effect, which is the warming of the Earth&amp;#39;s surface.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbon dioxide is the most well-known greenhouse gas and is considered the primary driver of climate change caused by human activities.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other greenhouse gases include methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and fluorinated gases such as hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), perfluorocarbons (PFCs), and sulfur hexafluoride (SF6).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These gases are released into the atmosphere through human activities such as burning fossil fuels, deforestation, and agriculture.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Greenhouse gases are important for maintaining the Earth&amp;#39;s temperature, but when their concentration in the atmosphere increases.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They can cause the Earth&amp;#39;s surface to warm up, leading to climate change and its associated impacts such as rising sea levels, more frequent extreme weather events, and changes in ecosystems&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
